{{refimprove|date=October 2012}}

'''Internet Party Line''' (or simply '''iParty''') was one of the first [[Internet phone|Internet telephony and conference]] software for [[Microsoft Windows]]. It was made by [[Intel]] and released as an experimental [[prototype]] in 1995.  It featured a push-to-talk method of sending audio, in which each received audio clip was played in order without mixing, regardless of multiple people talking simultaneously.  In this way, it addressed the problem of how to have an understandable group conversation in the face of large Internet latencies or low bandwidth.

Similar applications like iParty include [[Microsoft NetMeeting]] and [[VocalTec|VocalTec Internet Phone]]. Today Most of these older conference applications have been replaced by [[VoIP|VoIP applications]] such as [[Skype]].

